{"title_page": "James Brayshaw", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = James Brayshaw\n| female = \n| image = James Brayshaw.jpg\n| country = Australia\n| fullname = James Antony Brayshaw\n| nickname = JB, Jim, Jimbob, Jimmy\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1967|5|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Subiaco, Western Australia]], Australia\n| heightft = \n| heightinch = \n| heightm = \n| batting = Right-hand bat\n| bowling = Right-arm very slow\n| role = [[Batsman]]\n| club1 = [[Western Warriors|Western Australia]]\n| year1 = 1987\u20131990\n| club2 = [[Southern Redbacks|South Australia]]\n| year2 = 1990\u20131997\n| clubnumber1 = \n| deliveries = \n| columns = 2\n| column1 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches1 = 75\n| runs1 = 4,934\n| bat avg1 = 42.53\n| 100s/50s1 = 10/29\n| top score1 = 146\n| deliveries1 = 1,169\n| wickets1 = 10\n| bowl avg1 = 57.20\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 2/15\n| catches/stumpings1 = 43/0\n| column2 = [[List A cricket|List A]]\n| matches2 = 35\n| runs2 = 589\n| bat avg2 = 25.60\n| 100s/50s2 = 1/1\n| top score2 = 101*\n| deliveries2 = 409\n| wickets2 = 8\n| bowl avg2 = 40.00\n| fivefor2 = 0\n| tenfor2 = n/a\n| best bowling2 = 2/20\n| catches/stumpings2 = 12/0\n| date = 31 March\n| year = 2008\n| source = http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/australia/content/player/4202.html cricinfo.com\n}}\n\n'''James Antony Brayshaw (\"JB\")''' (born 11 May 1967) is an Australian media personality working in television for the [[Seven Network]] and radio for [[Triple M]]  and retired [[cricketer]]. For [[Seven Sport]] he hosts and calls test cricket during summer and [[Australian Football League|AFL]] on Saturday nights during winter.   \n\nBrayshaw worked for the [[Nine Network]] for 15 years, calling AFL, cricket and co-hosting [[AFL Footy Show|The Footy Show]].\n\nAs a cricketer he was known as '''Jamie Brayshaw'''. He is a former chairman of the [[North Melbourne Football Club]]. From 2011 to 2015 he was chairman of the [[Melbourne Renegades]] cricket team.\n\nBrayshaw is the son of former Western Australian cricketer and Australian rules footballer [[Ian Brayshaw]] and the brother of [[Mark Brayshaw]], a former player for the AFL club North Melbourne. \n\nAs of December 2018, Brayshaw has three nephews on AFL Lists at three clubs; [[Angus Brayshaw]] at the Melbourne Football Club. [[Andrew Brayshaw]] at the  Fremantle Football Club and Hamish Brayshaw at the West Coast Eagles Football Club.<ref>http://www.westcoasteagles.com.au/player-profile/hamish-brayshaw</ref> Mark Brayshaw is father of Angus, Andrew and Hamish.\n\n== Cricket career ==\nPlaying for [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]] and [[Western Australia cricket team|Western Australia]], Brayshaw had a career spanning almost a decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/player/4202.html|title=Jamie Brayshaw|website=Cricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref> In that time he was a consistent fielder, with 43 catches. Not only is he a two-time [[Sheffield Shield]] winner, this achievement was completed with two states and occurred on the teams' respective home grounds. In the 1987/1988 final, Brayshaw won with Western Australia at the [[WACA Ground]] and in the 1995/1996 final he won with South Australia at the [[Adelaide Oval]]. He would continue to play domestic cricket for one more season, before retiring at 30 years of age.\n\nPlaying in the 1995/1996 Sheffield Shield final (South Australia v Western Australia) at the Adelaide Oval, Brayshaw performed solidly with the bat, scoring 87 (run out) in the first innings and 66 (caught and bowled off [[Brad Hogg]]) in the second innings. Both teams fielded high quality players who have represented Australia at various levels. Some would go on to coach at state and national levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-25/where-were-you-when-south-australia-won-the-sheffield-shield/7276572|title=Where were you when South Australia last won the Shield?|date=25 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref> West Australia fielded players including [[Michael Hussey]], [[Justin Langer]], [[Tom Moody]], [[Damien Martyn]], [[Adam Gilchrist]], [[Jo Angel]], Brad Hogg and [[Brendon Julian]]. While South Australia fielded players including [[Greg Blewett]], [[Darren Lehmann]], [[Tim Neilsen]], [[Tim May]] and [[Jason Gillespie]]. The match ended in a draw, with a respectable performance from Adam Gilchrist 189 (not out) in the first innings,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/v/eYRlskFBOuU</ref> and as a consequence James and his South Australian teammates were the 1995/1996 Sheffield Shield premiers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/325419.html|title=Final, Sheffield Shield at Adelaide, Mar 30-Apr 3 1996 - Match Summary - ESPNCricinfo|website=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrayshaw also played in the 1987/1988 Sheffield Shield win for West Australia, but his performance with the bat was less successful. Scoring 24 off 104 balls (first innings) and 4 off 8 balls (second innings) and having the rare achievement of being caught by two international test captains, with [[Allan Border]] in the first innings and [[Ian Botham]] in the second innings<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/49/49746.html|title=The Home of CricketArchive|website=cricketarchive.com|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Media career ==\n\n===Early career===\nIn the 1990s, Brayshaw worked for the [[Seven Network]] in Adelaide. This included being a substitute sports anchor for the ''[[Seven News|Seven Nightly News]]'' bulletin and working on local football discussion programs, such as ''Footy Plus''. In early 1998 he was teamed up with [[Amanda Blair]] and Paul Gale on Adelaide's SAFM, which eventually became that city's number one rating breakfast show. One on-air incident at SAFM saw him covered in [[Adelaide Football Club]] bodypaint after the club he supports, [[Kangaroos FC|North Melbourne]], lost the [[1998 AFL Grand Final]] to them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/james-brayshaw/person/424429/biography.html|title=TV.com \u2013 James Brayshaw Biography|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\n\nIn 2001 his big break came as the host of the [[Seven Network]]'s [[The Ashes|Ashes]] ([[cricket]]) action with [[Jeff Thomson]], but later moved to the [[Nine Network]] when the [[Australian Football League]] was transferred. He became the nightly anchor for the ''[[National Nine News]]'' sport report, as well as contributing to other sports programs on the network, eventually becoming a regular commentator in both football and cricket coverage. In 2005, Brayshaw co-hosted ''[[Any Given Sunday (TV series)|Any Given Sunday]]'' with [[Garry Lyon]] and [[Sam Newman]].\n\nIn 2006, Brayshaw (along with Garry Lyon) replaced [[Eddie McGuire]] as host of ''[[The AFL Footy Show]]'', a position he held until the end of 2016. Additionally, with Lyon he co-hosted the morning sessions of the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]] in Melbourne. Apart from his television commitments, he works for radio station [[Triple M]], as a host and commentator of their [[Australian rules football]] coverage. He also worked as a full-time co-host on breakfast program ''[[The Cage (radio show)|The Cage]]'' before it was axed in 2007 and replaced with Pete & Myf. Previously he has been part of the Melbourne-based show via his home studio in the [[Adelaide Hills]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nBrayshaw was installed as chairman of the North Melbourne Football Club on 6 December 2007 after the club rejected the AFL's deal to permanently relocate to the Gold Coast.{{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nIn September 2007, Brayshaw announced that he was leaving ''[[The Cage (radio show)|The Cage]]'' to spend more time with his family \u2013 just before the program was cancelled due to high costs and poor ratings.\n\n===Channel 9 years=== \n\nBrayshaw also hosted ''[[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Sunday Footy Show]]'', alongside panelists [[Dermott Brereton]], [[Nathan Brown (Australian footballer, born 1978)|Nathan Brown]], [[Shane Crawford]] and [[Billy Brownless]]. He has also hosted the Australian version of ''[[Wipeout (2009 Australian game show)|Wipeout]]'' with [[Josh Lawson]].\n\nFor the duration of the 2010 Winter Olympic Games in Vancouver, Brayshaw took on a commentary role for various skiing events alongside [[Michael Kennedy (skier)|Michael Kennedy]], former international moguls skier, dual Winter Olympics coach and current CEO of [[Ski & Snowboard Australia]], in calling the moguls competition. Brayshaw teamed up with three-time Australian snowboard champion, [[Jay Onley]], to call the action from the Olympic snowboard competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1006902|title=Nine Wide World of Sports \u2013 Vancouver 2010 Experts & Opinions|accessdate=7 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716164830/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1006902|archivedate=16 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Brayshaw resigned from ''The Sunday Footy Show'' and was replaced by fellow ex-cricketer [[Simon O'Donnell]]. In addition, he commentated on events of the [[2012 London Olympics]] of which Nine had broadcast rights with [[Foxtel]].\n\nBrayshaw has also been involved in golf and [[cricket]] coverage for Nine.\n\nIn December 2016, it was announced that Brayshaw had left the Nine Network after contract negotiations broke down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/james-brayshaw-leaves-channel-nine-craig-hutchison-to-cohost-the-footy-show-20161204-gt3qam.html|title=Brayshaw leaves Nine, Hutchison to co-host The Footy Show|date=2016-12-04|website=The Age|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref>\n\n===Seven Network===\nIn February 2018, it was announced that Brayshaw would join the [[Seven Network]] as an AFL commentator to call Saturday night matches for the network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/02/james-brayshaw-joins-seven.html|title=James Brayshaw joins Seven|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|date=5 February 2018|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, it was announced that Brayshaw would host and commentate for [[Seven Sport]]'s coverage of Test cricket and the Big Bash League.\n\nIn addition to his work with Seven, Brayshaw currently (2018) co-hosts ''[[The Rush Hour Triple M|The Rush Hour]]'' on [[Triple M Melbourne]] with [[Billy Brownless]]. The show is broadcast weekdays in the drive-time slot. He also hosts Triple M's Saturday afternoon football program The Saturday Rub and calls Saturday afternoon football for the station subject to his commitments with Channel 7. Formerly he also contributed to Triple M's coverage of test cricket.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn an accident on 20 September 2006, his sister Sally was killed instantly after the facade of her garage collapsed on top of her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,23663,20456492-10229,00.html|title=Sister killed by falling bricks|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrayshaw and his wife Sarah have four sons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/afl/james-brayshaw-north-melbournes-putting-president/story-fn9lr6j4-1226397245489 |title=James Brayshaw North Melbourne's putting president |first=Michael |last=Warner |work= Herald Sun |date=16 June 2012}}</ref> On 23 October 2014, the couple announced their separation after 23 years of marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/james-brayshaw-and-wife-sarah-have-separated/story-fnn7ma1h-1227100193894|title=James Brayshaw splits from wife|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of South Australian representative cricketers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060819224551/http://www.adamsmanagement.com.au/news/_artists_single.asp?ID=37 James Brayshaw photo and profile]\n*[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/4202.html Cricinfo Profile \u2013 James Brayshaw]\n*[http://www.theage.com.au/news/tv--radio/allrounder-in-the-chair/2005/09/21/1126982068882.html The Age article \u2013 All-rounder in the chair]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box| before = [[Anthonie Ferreira]] | title = [[Nelson Cricket Club]]<br>Professional | after = [[Brendon Julian]] | years = 1989}}\n{{succession box|title=[[North Melbourne Football Club]] Chairman|before= Graham Duff |after= [[Ben Buckley]] |years=2007\u20132016}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brayshaw, James}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football commentators]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Australian cricket commentators]]\n[[Category:Kensington cricketers]]\n[[Category:North Melbourne Football Club administrators]]\n[[Category:People educated at Pembroke School, Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:South Australia cricketers]]\n[[Category:Triple M presenters]]\n[[Category:Western Australia cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Western Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = James Brayshaw\n| female = \n| image = James Brayshaw.jpg\n| country = Australia\n| fullname = James Antony Brayshaw\n| nickname = JB, Jim, Jimbob, Jimmy\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1967|5|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Subiaco, Western Australia]], Australia\n| heightft = \n| heightinch = \n| heightm = \n| batting = Right-hand bat\n| bowling = Right-arm medium\n| role = [[Batsman]]\n| club1 = [[Western Warriors|Western Australia]]\n| year1 = 1987\u20131990\n| club2 = [[Southern Redbacks|South Australia]]\n| year2 = 1990\u20131997\n| clubnumber1 = \n| deliveries = \n| columns = 2\n| column1 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches1 = 75\n| runs1 = 4,934\n| bat avg1 = 42.53\n| 100s/50s1 = 10/29\n| top score1 = 146\n| deliveries1 = 1,169\n| wickets1 = 10\n| bowl avg1 = 57.20\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 2/15\n| catches/stumpings1 = 43/0\n| column2 = [[List A cricket|List A]]\n| matches2 = 35\n| runs2 = 589\n| bat avg2 = 25.60\n| 100s/50s2 = 1/1\n| top score2 = 101*\n| deliveries2 = 409\n| wickets2 = 8\n| bowl avg2 = 40.00\n| fivefor2 = 0\n| tenfor2 = n/a\n| best bowling2 = 2/20\n| catches/stumpings2 = 12/0\n| date = 31 March\n| year = 2008\n| source = http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/australia/content/player/4202.html cricinfo.com\n}}\n\n'''James Antony Brayshaw (\"JB\")''' (born 11 May 1967) is an Australian media personality working in television for the [[Seven Network]] and radio for [[Triple M]]  and retired [[cricketer]]. For [[Seven Sport]] he hosts and calls test cricket during summer and [[Australian Football League|AFL]] on Saturday nights during winter.   \n\nBrayshaw worked for the [[Nine Network]] for 15 years, calling AFL, cricket and co-hosting [[AFL Footy Show|The Footy Show]].\n\nAs a cricketer he was known as '''Jamie Brayshaw'''. He is a former chairman of the [[North Melbourne Football Club]]. From 2011 to 2015 he was chairman of the [[Melbourne Renegades]] cricket team.\n\nBrayshaw is the son of former Western Australian cricketer and Australian rules footballer [[Ian Brayshaw]] and the brother of [[Mark Brayshaw]], a former player for the AFL club North Melbourne. \n\nAs of December 2018, Brayshaw has three nephews on AFL Lists at three clubs; [[Angus Brayshaw]] at the Melbourne Football Club. [[Andrew Brayshaw]] at the  Fremantle Football Club and Hamish Brayshaw at the West Coast Eagles Football Club.<ref>http://www.westcoasteagles.com.au/player-profile/hamish-brayshaw</ref> Mark Brayshaw is father of Angus, Andrew and Hamish.\n\n== Cricket career ==\nPlaying for [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]] and [[Western Australia cricket team|Western Australia]], Brayshaw had a career spanning almost a decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/player/4202.html|title=Jamie Brayshaw|website=Cricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref> In that time he was a consistent fielder, with 43 catches. Not only is he a two-time [[Sheffield Shield]] winner, this achievement was completed with two states and occurred on the teams' respective home grounds. In the 1987/1988 final, Brayshaw won with Western Australia at the [[WACA Ground]] and in the 1995/1996 final he won with South Australia at the [[Adelaide Oval]]. He would continue to play domestic cricket for one more season, before retiring at 30 years of age.\n\nPlaying in the 1995/1996 Sheffield Shield final (South Australia v Western Australia) at the Adelaide Oval, Brayshaw performed solidly with the bat, scoring 87 (run out) in the first innings and 66 (caught and bowled off [[Brad Hogg]]) in the second innings. Both teams fielded high quality players who have represented Australia at various levels. Some would go on to coach at state and national levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-03-25/where-were-you-when-south-australia-won-the-sheffield-shield/7276572|title=Where were you when South Australia last won the Shield?|date=25 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref> West Australia fielded players including [[Michael Hussey]], [[Justin Langer]], [[Tom Moody]], [[Damien Martyn]], [[Adam Gilchrist]], [[Jo Angel]], Brad Hogg and [[Brendon Julian]]. While South Australia fielded players including [[Greg Blewett]], [[Darren Lehmann]], [[Tim Neilsen]], [[Tim May]] and [[Jason Gillespie]]. The match ended in a draw, with a respectable performance from Adam Gilchrist 189 (not out) in the first innings,<ref>https://www.youtube.com/v/eYRlskFBOuU</ref> and as a consequence James and his South Australian teammates were the 1995/1996 Sheffield Shield premiers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/325419.html|title=Final, Sheffield Shield at Adelaide, Mar 30-Apr 3 1996 - Match Summary - ESPNCricinfo|website=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrayshaw also played in the 1987/1988 Sheffield Shield win for West Australia, but his performance with the bat was less successful. Scoring 24 off 104 balls (first innings) and 4 off 8 balls (second innings) and having the rare achievement of being caught by two international test captains, with [[Allan Border]] in the first innings and [[Ian Botham]] in the second innings<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/49/49746.html|title=The Home of CricketArchive|website=cricketarchive.com|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Media career ==\n\n===Early career===\nIn the 1990s, Brayshaw worked for the [[Seven Network]] in Adelaide. This included being a substitute sports anchor for the ''[[Seven News|Seven Nightly News]]'' bulletin and working on local football discussion programs, such as ''Footy Plus''. In early 1998 he was teamed up with [[Amanda Blair]] and Paul Gale on Adelaide's SAFM, which eventually became that city's number one rating breakfast show. One on-air incident at SAFM saw him covered in [[Adelaide Football Club]] bodypaint after the club he supports, [[Kangaroos FC|North Melbourne]], lost the [[1998 AFL Grand Final]] to them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/james-brayshaw/person/424429/biography.html|title=TV.com \u2013 James Brayshaw Biography|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\n\nIn 2001 his big break came as the host of the [[Seven Network]]'s [[The Ashes|Ashes]] ([[cricket]]) action with [[Jeff Thomson]], but later moved to the [[Nine Network]] when the [[Australian Football League]] was transferred. He became the nightly anchor for the ''[[National Nine News]]'' sport report, as well as contributing to other sports programs on the network, eventually becoming a regular commentator in both football and cricket coverage. In 2005, Brayshaw co-hosted ''[[Any Given Sunday (TV series)|Any Given Sunday]]'' with [[Garry Lyon]] and [[Sam Newman]].\n\nIn 2006, Brayshaw (along with Garry Lyon) replaced [[Eddie McGuire]] as host of ''[[The AFL Footy Show]]'', a position he held until the end of 2016. Additionally, with Lyon he co-hosted the morning sessions of the [[2006 Commonwealth Games]] in Melbourne. Apart from his television commitments, he works for radio station [[Triple M]], as a host and commentator of their [[Australian rules football]] coverage. He also worked as a full-time co-host on breakfast program ''[[The Cage (radio show)|The Cage]]'' before it was axed in 2007 and replaced with Pete & Myf. Previously he has been part of the Melbourne-based show via his home studio in the [[Adelaide Hills]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nBrayshaw was installed as chairman of the North Melbourne Football Club on 6 December 2007 after the club rejected the AFL's deal to permanently relocate to the Gold Coast.{{Citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\nIn September 2007, Brayshaw announced that he was leaving ''[[The Cage (radio show)|The Cage]]'' to spend more time with his family \u2013 just before the program was cancelled due to high costs and poor ratings.\n\n===Channel 9 years=== \n\nBrayshaw also hosted ''[[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Sunday Footy Show]]'', alongside panelists [[Dermott Brereton]], [[Nathan Brown (Australian footballer, born 1978)|Nathan Brown]], [[Shane Crawford]] and [[Billy Brownless]]. He has also hosted the Australian version of ''[[Wipeout (2009 Australian game show)|Wipeout]]'' with [[Josh Lawson]].\n\nFor the duration of the 2010 Winter Olympic Games in Vancouver, Brayshaw took on a commentary role for various skiing events alongside [[Michael Kennedy (skier)|Michael Kennedy]], former international moguls skier, dual Winter Olympics coach and current CEO of [[Ski & Snowboard Australia]], in calling the moguls competition. Brayshaw teamed up with three-time Australian snowboard champion, [[Jay Onley]], to call the action from the Olympic snowboard competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1006902|title=Nine Wide World of Sports \u2013 Vancouver 2010 Experts & Opinions|accessdate=7 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716164830/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1006902|archivedate=16 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Brayshaw resigned from ''The Sunday Footy Show'' and was replaced by fellow ex-cricketer [[Simon O'Donnell]]. In addition, he commentated on events of the [[2012 London Olympics]] of which Nine had broadcast rights with [[Foxtel]].\n\nBrayshaw has also been involved in golf and [[cricket]] coverage for Nine.\n\nIn December 2016, it was announced that Brayshaw had left the Nine Network after contract negotiations broke down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/james-brayshaw-leaves-channel-nine-craig-hutchison-to-cohost-the-footy-show-20161204-gt3qam.html|title=Brayshaw leaves Nine, Hutchison to co-host The Footy Show|date=2016-12-04|website=The Age|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref>\n\n===Seven Network===\nIn February 2018, it was announced that Brayshaw would join the [[Seven Network]] as an AFL commentator to call Saturday night matches for the network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/02/james-brayshaw-joins-seven.html|title=James Brayshaw joins Seven|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|date=5 February 2018|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, it was announced that Brayshaw would host and commentate for [[Seven Sport]]'s coverage of Test cricket and the Big Bash League.\n\nIn addition to his work with Seven, Brayshaw currently (2018) co-hosts ''[[The Rush Hour Triple M|The Rush Hour]]'' on [[Triple M Melbourne]] with [[Billy Brownless]]. The show is broadcast weekdays in the drive-time slot. He also hosts Triple M's Saturday afternoon football program The Saturday Rub and calls Saturday afternoon football for the station subject to his commitments with Channel 7. Formerly he also contributed to Triple M's coverage of test cricket.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn an accident on 20 September 2006, his sister Sally was killed instantly after the facade of her garage collapsed on top of her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,23663,20456492-10229,00.html|title=Sister killed by falling bricks|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrayshaw and his wife Sarah have four sons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/afl/james-brayshaw-north-melbournes-putting-president/story-fn9lr6j4-1226397245489 |title=James Brayshaw North Melbourne's putting president |first=Michael |last=Warner |work= Herald Sun |date=16 June 2012}}</ref> On 23 October 2014, the couple announced their separation after 23 years of marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/james-brayshaw-and-wife-sarah-have-separated/story-fnn7ma1h-1227100193894|title=James Brayshaw splits from wife|publisher=|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of South Australian representative cricketers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060819224551/http://www.adamsmanagement.com.au/news/_artists_single.asp?ID=37 James Brayshaw photo and profile]\n*[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/4202.html Cricinfo Profile \u2013 James Brayshaw]\n*[http://www.theage.com.au/news/tv--radio/allrounder-in-the-chair/2005/09/21/1126982068882.html The Age article \u2013 All-rounder in the chair]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box| before = [[Anthonie Ferreira]] | 